04657nam a22005895i 9780300145977DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001459777 a10.12987/97803001459772doi  a(DE-B1597)486658  a(OCoLC)1023987078  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aDS686.5b.T49 1995eb 7aHIS0480002bisacsh04a959.9/04/62221 aThompson, Mark R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Anti-Marcos Struggle :bPersonalistic Rule and Democratic Transition in the Philippines /cEvelyn S. Rawski, Mark R. Thompson. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Rules of Pre-Martial Law Philippine Politics -- t2. The Collapse of Philippine Democracy -- t3. Sultanistic Rule and the Demobilization of the Opposition -- t4. The Form, Not the Substance, of Democracy -- t5. Urban Terrorism after a Stolen Election -- t6. Boycott and a United Front -- t7. The Parliament of the Streets and Legislative Polls -- t8. The Snap Elections and the Fall of Marcos -- t9. Democratic Transition and Consolidation -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tSelected Bibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Philippine dictatorship of Ferdinand E. Marcos was characterized by family-based rule and corruption. This sultanistic regime-in which the ruler exercised power freely, without loyalty to any ideology or institution-had to be brought down because Marcos would never step down. In this book Mark Thompson analyzes how Marcos' opponents in the political and economic elite coped with this situation and why their struggle resulted in a transition to democracy through "people power" rather than through violence and revolution.Based on 150 interviews that Thompson conducted with key participants and on unpublished materials collected during his five trips to the Philippines, the book sheds new light on the transition process. Thompson reveals how anti-Marcos politicians backed a terrorist campaign by social democrats and then, after its failure, joined a "united front" with the communists. But when opposition leader Benigno S. Aquino, Jr., was assassinated in 1983, the politicians were able to draw on public outrage and challenge Marcos at the polls. The opposition's "moral crusade" brought down Marcos and enabled the new president, Corazon C. Aquino, to consolidate democracy despite the troubling legacies of the dictatorship. Thompson argues that the Philippines' long-standing democratic tradition and the appeal that honest government had to the Filipinos were important elements in explaining the peaceful transition process.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh1 aRawski, Evelyn S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311053799408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831105380140 cprintz978030006243440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014597740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300145977423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300145977/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre